li.p:
We have

  \begin{array}{lll}
  p = -\vvec, \amp q = 3\wvec, \amp r=2\vvec+3\wvec, \\
  s = 2\vvec-3\wvec, \amp t=-3\vvec-2\wvec, \amp
  u=-2\vvec+0.5\wvec, \\
  v = 3.5\vvec+1.5\wvec\text{.}
  \end{array}

We have

  \begin{array}{lll}
  p = -\vvec, \amp q = 3\wvec, \amp r=2\vvec+3\wvec, \\
  s = 2\vvec-3\wvec, \amp t=-3\vvec-2\wvec, \amp
  u=-2\vvec+0.5\wvec, \\
  v = 3.5\vvec+1.5\wvec\text{.}
  \end{array}

The appropriate linear system corresponds to the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 2 \amp -1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp -\frac{2}{3} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{2}{3} \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows we obtain {\mathbf 0} when the weights are chosen so that
\begin{alignedat}{2} c_1 \amp {}={} \frac23 c_3 \\ c_2 \amp {}={} -\frac23 c_3\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}

The totals consumed are expressed by the vector

  c\threevec{111}{140}{1.2} +
  d\threevec{120}{105}{1.0}\text{.}

We ask to write the vector \threevec{342}{385}{3.4} as a linear combination of the two cereal vectors. This leads to the augmented matrix
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 111 \amp 120 \amp 342 \\ 140 \amp 105 \amp 385 \\ 1.2 \amp 1.0 \amp 3.4 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This means that you had two servings of Frosted Flakes and one serving of Cocoa Puffs.

Now the augmented matrix is
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 111 \amp 120 \amp 250 \\ 140 \amp 105 \amp 200 \\ 1.2 \amp 1.0 \amp 4.0 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which represents an inconsistent system. This means that your sister must have eaten something else.

The totals consumed are expressed by the vector

  c\threevec{111}{140}{1.2} +
  d\threevec{120}{105}{1.0}\text{.}

Here we have
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 7 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which represents an inconsistent system and shows that \bvec cannot be written as a linear combination of \vvec_1, \vvec_2, and \vvec_3.

The augmented matrix is
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\ -1 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ -2 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{,}
which shows that \vvec_3=2\vvec_1+2\vvec_2.

solution.p:
We form the augmented matrix and find a triangular matrix that is row equivalent:
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 3 \amp 1 \amp k \\ -1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp 5 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rr|r} -1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp k-10 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This represents a consistent system when k=10.

li.p:
We have

  \twovec{x}{y} = 2\vvec_1 -3\vvec_2 =
  \twovec{1}{-4}\text{.}

As in the first part of this problem, we write

  \begin{alignedat}{2}
  x \amp {}={} \amp 2c+d \\
  y \amp {}={} \amp c+2d\text{.} \\
  \end{alignedat}

We want to solve
\twovec{x}{y} = c\vvec_1 + d\vvec_2 by constructing the augmented matrix and finding its reduced row echelon form.
\left[\begin{array}{rr|r} 2 \amp 1 \amp x \\ 1 \amp 2 \amp y \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}

Solve the linear system corresponding to the augmented matrix

  \left[\begin{array}{rr|r}
  2 \amp 1 \amp x \\
  1 \amp 2 \amp y \\
  \end{array}\right]\text{.}
